%S A087167 8925,32445,442365,151115727449904501489664
%N A087167 Numbers k such that sigma(k) - 2k = 6.
%C A087167 If odd m is in this sequence and 5 doesn't divide m, then m is an odd Weird number.
%C A087167 Any term x of this sequence can be combined with any term y of A141548 to satisfy the property (sigma(x)+sigma(y))/(x+y) = 2, which is a necessary (but not sufficient) condition for two numbers to be amicable. - _Timothy L. Tiffin_, Sep 13 2016
%C A087167 For k in A059609, 2^(k-1)*(2^k-7) is a term. - _Max Alekseyev_, Oct 11 2025
%D A087167 R. K. Guy, "Almost Perfect, Quasi-Perfect, Pseudoperfect, Harmonic, Weird, Multiperfect and Hyperperfect Numbers." B2 in Unsolved Problems in Number Theory, 2nd ed.New York:Springer- Verlag, pp. 45-53, 1994.
%H A087167 S. Benkoski, <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/2316276">Are All Weird Numbers Even?</a>, Problem E2308, Amer. Math. Monthly, 79 (7) (1972), 774.
%H A087167 W. Fang, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2207.12906">Searching on the boundary of abundance for odd weird numbers</a>, arXiv:2207.12906 [math.NT], 2022.
%H A087167 Carlos Rivera, <a href="http://www.primepuzzles.net/puzzles/puzz_233.htm">Puzzle 233. A little twist</a>, The Prime Puzzles & Problems Connection.
%H A087167 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/WeirdNumber.html">Weird Number</a>.
%e A087167 a(1)=8925 because sigma(8925)=2*8925+6 and 8925 is the first odd number such that sigma(n)-2n=6.
%t A087167 Do[If[OddQ[n] && DivisorSigma[1, n] - 2n == 6, Print[n]], {n, 2*10^9}]
%o A087167 (PARI) is(n)=sigma(n)==2*n+6; \\ _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Mar 09 2014
